n Rtreet,\nJersey ity. NX. J. for the purpose of electing Directors\nfor the ensuing year and acting upon such other busi\nvess as may he brought before the meeting.\n\n3\nThe ransfer bonks will he closed for this purpose on\nMay 12th and reopened on June 10th\nBy order of the Board of Directors\n\nALFRED NATHAN, Secretary\nEE i\nOFFICE OF\n\na7;\nAMATI GANMATED (OPPER (COMPANY.\n\n1061,\n42 Broadway, New York, April 20th, 1808\nNotice is hereby given that the stock certificate trans\nfer books of the Company will be closed on Monday, May\nJith, I18GR at 3 o'clock PP. M.. for the purpose of the\nAnnual Meeting of ithe Company, to be held June 1st,\nPOR, and that such hooks will be reopened on Tues\nday, June 23, 190%. st 10 o'clock A. M.\nA. H.  MELIN, Secretary.\n\n\n\n\n78 Ls\nni ey\n60\n391:\ni\ni\n\nBid. asked\n\n\nDVERTISEMENTS and subscriptions for The Tribune\nreceived at their Uptown Office, No. 1364 Broadwazy,\nbetween 36ih and 37th sts. until o'clock p. m. Adver\u2014\ntisements received at the following branch offices st\nregular office rates until 8 o'clock p. m.. viz: 264 KRth\n\u00aeve 5. cor. 23d st; 153 6th ave, cor. 12th si.; 32 Bast\n4th st. 207 West 324 =t.. between Tth and Sth aves\n263 West 125th st; 1238 34 ave, between 76th and 77th\n#26. 1026 34 ve, mear 61st gt; 1708 1st ave. near SOth\n\u00abtt 157 Past 125th st: TH6 Tremont ave. 650 3d ave.\nor ary American Digtrict Telegraph Office\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nby\n\ni\n62\n3\u00bb\n\na2\nB22\nTHE PETROLEUM FIELDS.\na]\nToa}\n\n\n\nOne big oil well of the gusher class came to the\nfront lzst week when the Wheeling Natural Gas\nCompany completed its test on the Marion Efaw\nfarm The well was drilled deeper on May 2\nznd started out at 670 harrels for the first tweighy\nfour hours znd 740 barrels for the second fu ar.\n1: 4i4 not long hold this heavy output, however, for\non the third dzy it fell off to 425 barrels But\neven at this. it ean only be regarded as a splendid\nproducer. The fourth sand, in which this well was\nstruck. hzs been irregular. and therefore operators\nhave not attacked it with the greatest confidence.\nOn Dunkard Creek, in the same district, several\ngood wells were found in this formation. but they\ndeclined rapidly and soon became pumpers. Im\nmediately following the good wells and close at\nhand. light pumpers znd even dusters were struck.\nThe Efaw well will be watched with considerable\nfnterest to see if it maintains itself better than\nthose which have preceded it. The heavy rains\nhave made the roads zlmost impassable and much\nrew work that was scheduled had to be abandoned\nuntil conditions change. Roane and Lincoln coun\nties were specially affected from this cause, as the\nwil districts are far removed from railroad facilities\n2nd work is maturally hampered. The Follanshee\nznd Holiday's Cove pools, Brook County, apppear\n10 hwgve been fully defined now, &s new work ocut\nside the MNMmits has brought out nothing beyond\njight affairs or gassers, and the chances for In\ncreasing the productive limits now secin to be very\nremote. Little or nothing of importance seems\n\u00abos have come to iight in the rest of the lower\nsouthwest field, but in the Boutheastern Ohio sec\nfion several good wells have been struck, but noth\ning of special tmportance. The mid-continent and\nIllinois fields present nothing for the week beyond\nthe ordinary, as there is the usua! number of fair\nwells and likewise of failures.\n\n\no 3 141 3\ni 1 138 8]\n3 5\n4 i i i 138\n2 81\n41% 7\nie 1} 281,\na\n\n\n\u201ces 40\n\n\n10 *enns L] extra,\n3\n68\nt \u201cee B32\n9 h rll 1 ant\n1100 101 {17 bias 2 oa\n190 011; 101 \u20184 do prefe a\n85 1008, 206 1015, i 2, Pp joa TnL im d a\n85 8b ke 4 200 Wabe is co Ee\n13\nsou x1 a Ba 150( do fr ogireanyss ALP\n\u2014ee of 83 82 3 1.700! Wes preferres 0 x\nLe ES i i,\nEe 82 15 West ferred. i\nSE a Wes ern Union \u2018Telegr iH\na i\nit 4 1s We le r Taos i\net fi Wheeling Lake rer\nSi EE\nx \u201c100! do 2d rred. IEEE po i\nue Tow wisconsin venir Cian i\nvo do Ir nr RA re\nASR preferred al\n357.23 Ss i\nH tal sales f Ey Ee g\nRefined petroleum is unchanged at \u00a3754c. in bar\nreis and $c. in bulk at New York. Philadelphia\nprices are on the basis of 5 points lower. Foreign\ngrices for refined oil are also unchanged: London\nspot, 6 8.164 zn imperial gallon; Antwerp, 21%\nfrancs per 100 kilos, and Bremen, \u00a305 marks per\nAs \u201cilng\nattempt to carry it into operation until the late\nfali. which probably means not until prices gen\nerallv shall be once more on the up grade.\nhe two great uncertainties the favorable res\nolution of which will most powerfully eon\ntribute to the full restoration of confidence and\nthe relatively speedy return of prosperity are the\ncrops and the Presidential election. The Pres\nidential campaign is not yet under way, but the\npresent outlook favors the nomination by the\nRepublican party of a man whose selection\nwould give general reassurance and of whose\nelection little doubt is expressed in any well\ninformed quarter. For the crops the prospect\nis at this date excellent, although no man can\ntell what a scason may bring forth in the way\nof drouth or frost or destruction by insects.\nWinter wheat, however, is close to the day when\ndanger to the growing crop may be declared\npast, and the government indication of May 1,\nwith its estimate of 428,000,006 bushels, com\nparing with last year's harvest of 405,000,060\nbushels, virtually assures a bounteous crop,\nwhile weather conditions are as yet favorable\nto the prosp-cts of spring wheat and the vast\ncorn crop, and of cotton, for the surplus of all\nof which crops there is likely to be a foreign\ndemand.\nHere and there are indications of a lifting of\nthe cloud of commercial and industrial depres\nsion, one of last week's signs being the record\ning of a smaller number of failures than for\nseveral weeks preceding, and bank clearings\nalso gave some encouragement in their rather\nlarger volume. Against these considerations is\nthe fact of the continuance of heavy receipts of\ncash from interior points, s2nt here because\nit cannot he profitably emploved at home. The\nmon=y conditions are those aiways experienced\nafter a panic\u2014idle funds heaped up until the\namount is enormous; then with the siow return\ning of confidence the cautious and discriminat\ning investment of some of the money in bonds,\nthe stage now reached; then strength and ac\ntivity and a broadening tendency in the stock\nmarket, with the continuance of the grewth of\nconfidence, and finally the venturing again of\nmoney in industrial and commercial commit\nments and the full revival of business. As the\ncountry is so much larger in a business way\nthan in previous post-panic periods, the store\nof idle funds in the banks is probably no heav\nier relatively than at corresponding dates in\nthe past, and the size of the surplus reserve of\nthe Associated Banks of New York, now in ex\ncess of $63,000,000, is not to be wondered at.\nThat enormous surplus\u2014and the banks of New\nYork are not singular in their condition of ab\nnormal ease\u2014and the absence of demand for\nfunds for business use account for the nominal\nloaning rates for money at this centre and\nmake negligible matter, from the point of view\nof possible money stringency, the withdrawal\nof many millions this month by the government\nand the probable resumption soon of the gold\nexport movement, foreign exchange rates hav\ning within the last few days once more ad\nvanced almost to the level at which shipments\nto Paris, on the triangular basis, may profitably\nbe arranged.\nfor the otle.\nsitjeg Yor the Wwoek. *Uuliste 0 ag\ntn nlisted i\nI a\nSR\nTHE FINANCIAL MARKETS\n\nTHE FINANCIAL MARKETS\nCONTINUED ADVANCE IN STOCKS UNDER HEAVY\nBUYING BY. POWERFUL INTERESTS.\nler pie ney\nBER\nRccord Transactions in Bonds\u2014Business Not Improving, but Sentiment\nMore Confident\u2014Crop Outlook.\n1\nCONTINUED ADVANCE IN STOCKS UNDER HEAVY\nBUYING BY. POWERFUL INTERESTS.\nRecord Transactions in Bonds\u2014Business Not Improving, but Sentiment\nMore Confident\u2014Crop Outlook.\nTHE WEEK IN WALL STREET.\nBit Mex\nkt recession, believing that it was certain to\nee\ni i fs. 3\noccur because the continuous advance during the\nprevious three weeks had amply discounted the\nimprovement which had been made in general\nbusiness conditions, have not yet seen their ex\npectation realized. Instead, the market during\nthe week just ended has made further progress\ntoward higher levels, ending the period with\nprices in the main the best of the year. There\nhas been covering of shorts on a good scale as\nthe advance has proceeded, but the impelling\nforce under the market has been the heavy buy\ning for account of powerful interests, buying\nwhich is apparently related to the railroad\nfinancing projects which are soon to be pre\nsented in the form of bond issues: for a strong\nstock market is an important aid in the distribu\ntion of bonds. Therefore, it may be that even\nhigher prices will be seen this week and that the\npace will not ease until after the bringing out of\nthe T'nion Pacific bond issue, which is expected\nto be for $530,000.000. The sweeping success of\nthe Pennsyivania Railroad's loan, in addition to\nproviding for the company funds for the carry\ning on its improvement work, distinctly ben\nefited the general situation. in demonstrating\nthat the investing public had regained confidence\nsufficiently to buy high grade securities, and the\noffering to be made by the Union Pacific is ex\npected to have a like double significance. Since\nthe Pennsylvania issue was brought out the\nbond market has been increasingly active, at ad\nvancing prices, the sales on Friday of last week\nhaving been $8.000000 par value, the largest\nday's business in many months, while in the two\nhours of trading on the following day the trans\nactions were on an even more extensive scale.\nAlany railroads are in need of money and many,\nnow that investors are once more entering the\nbond market, will offer to those investors an\nopportunity to purchase their securities. The\nresponse, however, will be proportioned to the\nattractiven\u2014ss of the several issues, from the\npoint of view, first, of safety and then of yield,\nin comparison with the high standard of the\nPennsylvania bonds. Few of the issues here\nafter to ba presented. it may be added, will have\nthe advantage of a foreign market, as did the\nPennsylvania loan and as the Union Pacific issue\nis expected to have.\n\n\n\n1\nfos\n\n053,\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\ni\n\n\ni\n~gzes\nStagnation continues in trade and industry\nthroughout the country, and nowhere is any\nconsiderable increase in prodnction or enlarge\nment of buving demand reported Yet the feel\ning is no longer that of unrelieved depression.\nIn the textile industry, for example, although\nthe mills are stili running at greatly reduced\ncapacity, sentiment is said to be much more\ncheerful. The steel industry is not reviving as\nvet, but if the efforts of the railroads to avall\nthemselves of the extreme money market ease\nfor fioating bond issues shall meet with success\nthere will before long be funds in hand which\nwill be used in part for the purchase of steel\nrails and structural steel. A beginning in the\ndirection of renewed general buying on the part\nof the raiiroads appears to have been made in\nthe orders placed last week by several roads for\nlocomotives There has been no change made\nbv the steel manufacturing companies in their\nprice schedules. and the impression 18 wide\nspread that concessions in prices would be\nquickly followed by the placing of large orders\nfor rails and other material. although until busi.\nnese shall revive and returns from freight traf\nfic shall increase the railroads are not likely to\njudge it expedient to spend much money for pur\nposes cother than those absolutely necessary.\nThe pig iron makers, at their adjourned meet\ning last week. announced that no agreement ex\njsted for maintaining rates, and accordingly can\nnow cut prices at will in the competition for\nbusiness-\u2014as indeed thev have been for some\ntime reported to be doing.\na\nad\nih 508,\n163\nR R\nThe railroads, on the other hand, have been\ncherizshing the hape of being able ta increase\ntheir revenues in a time of profound business\ndepression. when zlmost all commodities are de\nclining in price. by raising their rates for the\ncarriage of those commodities. That plan, a\nnovelty in political economy, could not be made\neffective, even though sanctioned by tha Wash\nington authorities, unless adopted by all of the\nroads in a2 given territory, and its enforcement\nin the face of opposition of shippers would cause\na recrudescence of the anti-railroad agitation,\nwhich of late has pretty weil subsided. There\nis reason to believe that the small roads in\ntrunk line territory have not been brought into\niine in support of the proposition, and from\nvarious points in the last few days have come\nreports of the shippers raising angry protests;\nand perhaps for ihese reasons the trunk line\npresidents, while affirming their belief in the\n\nsoundness of the plan, have concluded not to\nattempt to carry it into operation until the late\nfali. which probably means not until prices gen\nerallv shall be once more on the up grade.\nhe two great uncertainties the favorable res\nolution of which will most powerfully econ\ntribute to the full restoration of confidence and\nthe relatively speedy return of prosperity are the\ncrops and the Presidential election. The Pres\nidential campaign is not yet under way, but the\npresent outlook favors the nomination by the\nRepublican party of a man whose selection\nwould give general reassurance and of whose\nelection little doubt is expressed in any well\ninformed quarter. For the crops the prospect\nis at this date excellent, although no man can\ntell what a scason may bring forth in the way\nof drouth or frost or destruction by insects.\nWinter wheat, however, is close to the day when\ndanger to the growing crop may be declared\npast, and the government indication of May 1,\nwith its estimate of 428,000,606 bushels, com\nparing with last year's harvest of 405,000,060\nbushels, virtually assures a bounteous crop,\nwhile weather conditions are as yet favorable\nto the prosp-cts of spring wheat and the vast\ncorn crop, and of cotton, for the surplus of all\nof which crops there is likely to be a foreign\ndemand.\nHere and there are indications of a lifting of\nthe cloud of commercial and industrial depres\nsion, one of last week's signs being the record\ning of a smaller number of failures than for\nseveral weeks preceding, and bank clearings\nalso gave some encouragement in their rather\nlarger volume. Against these considerations is\nthe fact of the continuance of heavy receipts of\ncash from interior points, sent here because\nit cannot he profitably emploved at home. The\nmon=y conditions are those aiways experienced\nafter a panic\u2014idle funds heaped up until the\namount is enormous; then with the siow return\ning of confidence the cautious and discriminat\ning investment of some of the money in bonds,\nthe stage now reached; then strength and ac\ntivity and a broadening tendency in the stock\nmarket, with the continuance of the growth of\nconfidence, and finally the venturing again of\nmoney in industrial and commercial commit\nments and the full revival of business. As the\ncountry is so much larger in a business way\nthan in previous post-panic periods, the store\nof idle funds in the banks is probably no heav\njer relatively than at corresponding dates in\nthe past, and the size of the surplus reserve of\nthe Associated Banks of New York, now in ex\npa Ee oF DEITNI EE TYEE TT TEE YEE TET TT Ow Tree. nay\nBANK EXCHANGES; SALES RECORDED.\nThe bank exchanges of the New York learing\nHouse and the stocks sold on